Republican Strategy for Resistance to Obama's Re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat fraud in elections.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter myth, arguing that cases of falsifying elections in the United States are more rare than those resulting from lightning strikes.
Moreover, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partly discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have since 2009 enacted laws that make registration or voting more difficult.
This phenomenon took on new dimensions after the November 2010 elections, which brought 675 new seats to Republicans in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the right to vote in 41 states were passed in 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require the voter to present a photo ID and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register voters on the day of expression of will, and withdraw the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present an identity card with a photograph.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities have hastened to extend this practice to other states as well.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to present photo identification cards in 34 states.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached voting age, do not have an identity card with a photograph issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters did not have such a document in 2012.
However, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds $100.
New restrictions disproportionately affect youth, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 years of age and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo identity card.
But that's not all.
Electoral students who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their educational establishment in several states.
At the same time, the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mostly for Republicans, to use the licences issued by these clubs for voting.
Until 2004, no state required proof of American citizenship to vote.
This was the first time such a claim had been introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are apparently aimed at limiting the vote of Latin Americans.
Two thirds of Latin American voters are believed to vote in favour of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators initiated laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight states.
They also limited the right of individuals or groups to assist those wishing to register.
This restriction has not passed without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to register about 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent drop in the new voter registration rate in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have enacted laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33 per cent of the voters who voted early were African Americans, although the latter constituted only 13 per cent of the total number of voters in the state.
The same was true of Latin American nationals.
Representing only 11 per cent of the electorate, they accounted for 24 per cent of citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who make up 76% of the electorate, only 46% of the electorate voted early.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws were vetted by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This has resulted in a partial limitation of the negative effects.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the production of a photo identity card.
Nevertheless, the new rules that have come into force will undoubtedly impede the exercise of the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Democrat critics condemn the bias of laws that have been passed, seeing them as clearly oriented towards influencing the 2012 election results in key states.
The Brennan Center ' s 2011 report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral board to win the presidential election.
It is too early to state with confidence that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partly discredit the system of American democracy.
