Higgs' boson in detail
The previous summer, it was reported that scientists might have been able to locate the Higgs boson that caused a real agitation - and not without cause.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, not much.
In addition, it is the last particle predicted in the Standard Model - our best, or in any case, the “best imperfect” description of the nature and behaviour of matter - but which has not previously been able to be detected in an experimental way.
But physics isn't quite sure it's the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we're dealing with a really new particle and that it's very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical convention in Kyoto seem to confirm this, although some data are not yet available for full confidence.
Let's imagine it's about the Higgs boson, because the odds of being wrong seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law absolutely inevitable, saying that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way around this rule, don't even try too hard, or you'll hurt yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of this nature: the principle of Paulie's exclusion, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same point in time if they are in the same "quantum state" is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens called ferries who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
Another is bosons, a vile gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything — at least this principle, which means that they may find themselves in the same place at the same time.
According to the website (by the way, a completely extraordinary) Particle Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories, these bosons are in turn divided into two groups: the mesons we are not going to talk about here, and the "particles of force" by which the main forces of nature are spread and to which the Higgs boson in some way refers.
These very bosons, it should be stressed, are not all exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it's because of one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or "part of light", which is an electromagnetic messenger.
Indeed, when one particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" an electromagnetic field in this particular location, roughly like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "violation" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of the "power carrier".
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the only difference that for this boson to appear, there must be a "violation" of another field, the Higgs field.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very and very high energy, as if it were a frozen pond whose surface could only shake a very large stone.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator, like the one operating in CERN, the Big Adron Collider, which is a 27 km diameter ring!, to achieve such huge energies.
An electromagnetic field analogy is also useful to explain the relationship between Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with an electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold onto the refrigerator itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who interact have mass, while others (as photon, by the way) do not.
So, what's "can bring" all this research, is Ms. Plamondon asking?
In science, they are used to test the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to find a discrepancy between observations and predictions of the CM.
In addition, some of them are eager to see such a discrepancy revealed, so the slightest inconsistency can open the door to "new physics" and shut up some of the Model's holes.
The latter, to be said, still has significant shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oy!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oy!).
But we haven't found any such differences in CERN yet.
Impact
The benefits of these studies for the daily life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it does not exist.
See, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell's labs couldn't even guess what revolution their work would be.
They anticipated their applications in science, but no more than that.
Indeed, the already deceased physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell's Laboratories, where a laser was invented in 1960, and who himself designed the first continuous laser (previously impulse) in 1962, said that the laser was originally viewed as more of a "laboratory gadget".
Imagine...
In addition, an application could be found for the tools accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not its original purpose at all, now serves as an eye for all digital cameras in the world and has won the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Adron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
