Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties with commissions to process them.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, there is a clear political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudony), is simultaneously a virtual currency (but converted into dollars, euro ...) and a protected BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows file exchanges between participants of the same level.
Some 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers online.
Several thousand sites take bitcoins to make donations or as a payment medium.
The rate of Bitcoin, reaching a maximum of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning today to about ten dollars (the rates are listed on Bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the world's exchange of real money or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB), in its virtual currency report published in October, became interested in the system.
He describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with a dollar or euro" and "like ordinary currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as "credits" used to promote in video games that are earned in the game process or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The Facebook social network has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations always control and process a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are both book holders, auditors, issuers of currency, buyers and sellers.
How does the network function?
Each transaction between two users actually occurs between two e-mail addresses, like e-mail.
Only for each new payment can the user choose another address, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed, using a double key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that bitcoins used in the deal do exist in a public ledger distributed throughout the network.
A key step is the registration of a new transaction in this book.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical task sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, receives the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the hash phase of the file, that is, converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" all together.
The aim is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (multiple zeros at the beginning).
Once this number has been found, the other nodes easily verify that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be unrarely linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user would want to pay twice the same money in less than ten minutes, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed because they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoin.
To avoid inflation, the award is regularly divided in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divided to one hundred million, leaving a further reserve...
