Poland and space.
Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has participated actively in a number of Agency projects over the following years.
But the path to space Poland started a lot earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were involved in space flights, but this was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who on 6 December 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Space Science" at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory.
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Luis Hirsch Award for Induction into Space.
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899–1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and space science.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned space promoter, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the opposite side of the Moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway dredger equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as did the details of the project.
It's not even clear that a rocket should have been used to disperse or to stop the trolley.
Information about this drezine is only known from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has begun to think about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Weapons Technology Section with the cooperation of Professors Mázyslav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzytsky.
Remaining materials show that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket, proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in a specialized press, and the following year the work of the "Aerobic torpedo missile and the aerial bomb" by author Lelivi-Cjioblocchi came out.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war itself, all military missile projects were handled by the Temporary Scientific and Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next research work on space science appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of society is in the November 1954 issue of Problem magazine, which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich offered to organize a society that would be involved in space activities.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has tried to join an international federation of astronautics (founded in 1951), and as early as autumn, the PAA became a valid member.
The following year, the first president of PAA, Kazimez Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became the vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of a highly successful RM meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologyzna), which was the first Polish missile to perform a scientific study.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, capable of crossing a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
An improved version of the RM-1A was subsequently built, and a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested on the Bledov Desert in the summer of 1959.
The missile was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could have crossed 14.5 km, and its mission was to observe the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The first RM-type missiles were succeeded by the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was conceived as two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed which varied the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A missile had a volume of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1V had a volume of 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C had a volume of 0.62L.
All three types had a maximum range of 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, a Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute and its first flight trials began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket, with an initial weight of 380 kg, was capable of bringing a useful weight of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
Mention should also be made of Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
