Inflating of balloons, bananas and circus
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com portal, which conducts an annual poll on the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd decision or project from the EU workshop".
"We have been inspired by this latest event in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 per cent quota for women in the administration of major European companies," said Prada questionnaire organizer Patrick Nager.
Among the absurdities already nominated is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to combine the rate of premiums for men and women.
So far, women have had benefits for life insurance because they are objectively less at risk for insurance companies.
"Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be put forward by people for the competition before the end of this year.
The vote itself will take place before the end of February 2013, said Nager.
The controversial EU regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of bio-components to fuel, resulting in damage to nature, and the prohibition of the use of reliable mercury degrees only because they contain a relatively small amount of hazardous substances, or a directive on the size of a cage for chickens, which has resulted in significant egg prices this year.
The actual ban on the use of the term “bourbread oil” or the removal of classic light bulbs from the sale were also criticized.
Quality bananas must be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European machinery often makes a decision under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually protected by a State or a group of States (the Czech Republic is now even at risk of defending the demands of its banks).
The interests of the lobby are such that, for example, the top-quality bananas in the European Union should have reached a length of 14 centimetres and did not dare to display "anomalous curvature".
In doing so, the European Commission justified the fact that it only harmonizes existing fragmented national rules that made trade more difficult.
The EU, despite the resistance of some States, has nevertheless relaxed the standards for fruit and vegetables, citing that existing directives will lead to waste of products.
Last year's EU regulation that selling balloons must be given a warning that children under the age of eight cannot inflate them without adult supervision may also be a candidate for the poll.
The EU has turned to American studies, according to which balloons in the game are a potential cause of death of children by suffocation.
This restriction now applies to children under 14 years of age, who are not allowed to blow in marquee duds.
Funny ideas are born at home, too.
The rule concerning European officials themselves was absurd: anyone who held an official position in the EU could not, given the sensitivity of the topic for Greece, use the name of Macedonia, but should instead say “BürM” (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The Bankovnípoplatky.com portal, in cooperation with the Liberal Economists' Association “The Principle of Non-intervention” (Laissez Faire), proposed for voting, in addition to several absurd rules mentioned above, such as the EU regulation on the amount of food stocks on the territory of a Member State.
The EU has established a maximum stock of food that may be in the Czech Republic on the date of its accession to the European Union.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the established amounts of canned mushrooms, for which it was liable to a large fine.
The questionnaire was also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea and the idea of granting subsidies for applications for subsidies.
But these ideas arose in Prague, not Brussels.
"We're at a disadvantage because we don't have the sea.
Ask for compensation from the European Union," said then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (CSDP) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that there was a high yield of grain in the country and, as a result of the so-called intervention procurement, the State had full stockpiles of stocks that had to be removed.
For the fact that the Czech Republic is far from ports, the EU, according to Palas, had to pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission met the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grains from landlocked countries.
Grants for the grant were offered to villages by the Ministry of Regional Development, led by Minister Pavel Nemz (US-DEU), in particular such grants were to be drawn up for a grant application from Brussels.
EU: Curious regulations are the exception
While regulations in member States are easily criticized, EU regulatory efforts, as well as better functioning and development of the European Union, are considered by many experts to be more worthy of recognition.
A major problem, in the view of the experts, is the drawing of EU grants for projects that do not even imply a commonality with deepening European integration, but which Member States have achieved in the budget debate.
It causes emotion among the Czechs and that, as in other European Union countries, the Czech Republic should fight in Brussels for the right to specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win this competition.
Although the Czechs, after six years of fighting with the Germans and the Austrians, retained the name "Olomowsky cheeses", the "Tuzem rum", whose tradition in our country dates back to the 19th century, was to be renamed "Tuzemak".
Only products from cane distillate, not sugar beet, can be called rum.
The official list of EU-registered products, along with the world-famous "feta" and "gorgonzola" cheeses, marzipan of German Lubek or Parm ham, has already been found, for example, to be carlovarian suhari, pottery and thrashbon carp, and zhuetzek hmel.
The EU’s trademark can also be proud of the Pardubic carrot and the Gorzy tubers.
People want me to protect the Republic, but I'm an amateur, says Okamura.
Mr. Senator, how does a man come to run for president?
I don't think about becoming a senator or president myself.
If everything was working in the country without a problem, I wouldn't be running anywhere.
But I can't stand to see the country embezzling over the past 20 years, thieves poking around, people raising taxes and retirement ages.
I had no ambition to be a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, I try to find a way to change it.
And since I am now forty years old and an independent person who is not a member of any party, I have no other way to influence things than to run for senator or president.
You got into the Senate, but soon you went to the presidential castle.
Don't you turn your back on the people who chose you?
I always said I'd fight for the presidential castle depending on the outcome of the Senate election.
I later clarified that if I were elected senator, I would run for president.
My goal is not the post, the post is the tool by which I can exercise my views.
That's why I need the greatest influence and the greatest authority.
But the difficulty is not only that as a nation, we snort in our own bar or television, but are ready to trample on anyone who tries to make a difference.
To this is added the media, which defame a person, and which confuse freedom of speech with freedom of lie.
For example, I was told that I was giving bribes to journalists, or that I was an advisor to Jiri Paroubek.
Let's move on to your views.
The fight for the presidential castle you started with theories about the material and criminal responsibility of politicians and back-to-back property declarations worth more than 20 million.
To do so, it is necessary to change the law.
You don't have that power as president, and only a whole Senate can propose laws.
How do you want to do that?
When I lobbied as a citizen for the guided tour to become a free enterprise, it was able to move forward.
The problem is politics - when someone comes with a good offer on the left or right, they are deliberately obstructed, and that discourages citizens.
As an independent, non-partisan, I have a much greater potential to receive support from all parliamentary parties.
My advantage is that I can take from each party what is best for our country and apply it without looking back on the dogmats.
Do you think you're more of a right-wing or left-handed person?
From a Czech point of view, I think I'm more of a left-wing person.
It doesn't matter to me, a little to the left or a little to the right.
It's important to me that we go forward.
It's not about someone who's right, but someone who's left, I want to bring people together.
I will always support any good decision for society whether it is proposed by the HRCM or the HDP, and I will also oppose the bad idea.
You get angry when someone says you're a populist.
But don't you prove it by what you said?
When you create a business plan for a firm, you also have some ideal goals and views.
And that's what you're trying to get close to.
You can call it populism, but all the proposals I'm talking about are already functioning in the world, or they're being spoken of by eminent experts.
But without parliamentary support, you'll only have slogans.
And with that, you won't last long in politics.
Or do you think that when you go out to people and talk to them, you will be able to enforce criminal and material liability?
I don't have another chance.
Only to persuade politicians, journalists and the public and try to lure them to their side so that we can achieve ours.
If I had been elected President, it would not have been a problem to organize a live television broadcast in which I would call on the presidents of parliamentary parties to legitimize material and criminal responsibility for politicians, public servants, judges and prosecutors.
And if they refuse, they'll have to tell you why they don't want to.
If there is a strong individual who would speak of abuse, it would be possible to exert pressure on the political scene.
Take the president's direct election - it was a tribute to public pressure.
I'm telling you directly that I'm an amateur, not a genius or an intellectual.
I try to find allies to defend my beliefs and views.
I'm just a political starter, and for my program, I'm gonna try to get the majority's support.
I'm trying to move things on my own; if that fails, I'll be done in six years and I'll be back in the private sector.
It kind of sounds like Okamura's supposed to save the Czech Republic.
I'm no savior.
I know I'm not doing anything alone, so I've bypassed a number of famous people with an offer to run for Senate.
I went to Radim Yanchure, he refused because of the volume of work.
I also at least supported the ongoing investigation of journalist Jan Lorenzov, who discovered fraud with light fuel oil products.
I put forward my candidacy because people are really unhappy, but now I feel like I'm on the scales.
Sixty percent of the people did not go to the election, and most of those who went to the establishment.
There's only two of us independent in the Senate.
People have chosen the Senate in such a way that changes will be difficult to implement.
Despite this, I will fight for my views, such as direct election of mayors and governors.
Are you thinking about the basis of your own party?
I haven't thought about it yet, because I don't have time to test the purity of every potential supporter's past, and I don't have any money for it.
There's no money for the presidential campaign, only 20,000 kroner in my transparent account.
You don't have any money?
You're talking about property declarations, and what's your own business with that?
Personal property is estimated at approximately 60 million.
I have a plot in Prague worth about 25 million, a ten million apartment, another eight million apartment, a collection of artworks of about 10 million, Aston Martin for 3.5 million, and Schcode Superb for a million, and a few more million in the account.
By the way, I had Aston-Martin because it was my boy's dream - I always liked James Bond, who drove, was gallant with women, and at the same time fought against scoundrel and lawlessness.
You drive Aston Martin, own $60 million in property, and you don't have any money for the campaign?
You say you want to change the Republic, but you don't want to invest your own money in it.
That's not very convincing.
I don't have $15 million for the campaign.
Am I supposed to be in debt?
I've already invested $2.5 million in the campaign.
The fact that I have no sponsors suggests that my program is not as interesting.
And I don't have to pay for the campaign out of my pocket.
The campaign costs are basically going to cover Senator's salary.
But with that money, I wouldn't live, for example, to pay my son for an English school that costs 30,000 a month.
If I just wanted to make money, I wouldn't be running anywhere.
So you're going to be doing business so you can live?
Didn't you say you'd cut down on this activity?
But it doesn't depend on the salary.
As I promised, I have reduced my activities in part.
For example, the managing director of the travel agency will be my deputy in the spring.
People would have wanted me to be a silver-free man who would have kept the Republic.
But I have to live on something, too.
How much, as an entrepreneur, are you used to getting monthly?
Two hundred to four hundred thousand, which is what I'm getting.
And if I were president, I'd finish my business.
