The MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not just in the imagination - on the example of Speykenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photographs
"I think this building is fun, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again," says Lisette Verhaig, passing on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist in a nearby large enterprise, thinks, "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself, why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad, and e-books.
No one's going to such old-fashioned libraries now, right?
Speykenisse, a minor bedroom under Rotterdam, has an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate situation, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro notes, in the form of painted miniatures made of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And that's when the town's fathers realized they had the only chance to beat the statistics: build a library here!
Wine Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau of MVRDV, the master of bold column diagrams and author of witty, sometimes even cynical, structures, treated the task with his usual undisturbedness and appeared in a contest audition in 2003 with five books under the mouse and a grin on his face.
And while the members of the jury were puzzled to look around and shrug their shoulders, the daring Maas folded out of his original gift a pyramid in size and concluded the speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Respect citizens!"
Here it is, my proposal: "The Book Mountain" in Speykenisse, the so-called Bukenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, grew.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground garage, supermarket, postage and several adjacent housing units and townships for a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Book Mountain was awarded the second award of the 2012 Best Library of the Netherlands.
The project also participates in the 2012 National Dutch Woodwork Competition.
Thus, a faceless suburb that had previously been able to offer nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall whose white facades suggest a milk plant has become richer on one modern piece of architecture.
But most importantly, Speykenisse has the first cultural public building in the history of this town.
A Long Way to the Book
First impression: Eldorado's book under a cheese cap.
There's only one elevator in the middle of the mountain range, because real fans of architecture and reading would prefer to explore this area on foot.
Exposed from all sides - light and easy to see, floors of burnt brick and elegant street lights unmistakably create a sense of public urban square.
The urban environment is re-established perfectly.
The look is unwittingly looking for benches, dogs, and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere, books, books, books.
"Odinary bookshelves stand along facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless," says Winy Maas.
We put the classical configuration of the space on its head and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The internal space of the bookmount is used skillfully: the centre houses offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental centre and technical facilities.
The black bookshelves, which serve as the finer walls, the parapets, and the staircases, are particularly pleased.
Their species, texture, and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and builders are lost in guesses as to what this unknown material is.
"We sought to work with secondary materials," explains Yop Trauborst, the project manager representing the Speykenisse community, as required by the standard.
And one day at a farm in Frisland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years now, artificial fibre material of millimetre thickness has been used as a root lining in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It's cheap and saves time.
Tiny textiles serve one or two seasons, and can then be discarded.
For the library, this painting, for the first time in this volume, was compressed in a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbauplastic (KLP) turns into dark, homogeneous, durable material, which smells a little like a new car and a little sneaker.
The top is led by 105 steps.
Whoever crosses the road nearly 500 metres long will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquets and tree ficus in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
Cost of a new soul
"It's hard to believe, but this building, despite many glass surfaces, is a model environmental project," Trouborst says.
The heat of the ground shall be used to heat and cool it.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even in clear days the sun enters only briefly.
Large farms of glued wood, perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take over most of the sunlight.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The remaining protection is provided by fully automatic roll curtains.
Stefan Spermon, a skeptic from the IT field mentioned above, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was here as well.
Also, traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogard, who called Bukenberg "the soul of Speykenisse, who was long missed."
Reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate a book from his own congregation.
These books were to take up empty seats on the shelves of the yet-to-full library - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The regiments are forced to the top.
"There's nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Vini Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident is now connected in some way to this new house.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it only serves for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV was able to accomplish the royal task, which on professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Speykenisse wrote his literary history.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
It's just the starting point for building an identity.
Sabo: "Germans should play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on recognition of Palestine.
Stephen Sabo, an expert on US-Europe relations, believes that Berlin, by doing so, balances on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained in the vote to establish a no-fly zone.
NATO eventually carried out this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The point is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, from a policy that the US has so-called ruled to a German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent unified policy.
Thus, the Germans find themselves again between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're just trying to find their role, but they're on the road to "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy as France or the United Kingdom pursues.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
This is a willingness to take a position in its national interest that is not dependent on the position of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, i.e. on exports and links to certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests were largely different from those of other major States, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the position in the Middle East conflict and the United Nations vote?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to insult the public and elites in Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't put too much emphasis on it, it's not a totally one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the German calculations.
Did Germany harm its relationship with the United States by abstaining from making important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the United States, understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
Indeed, it signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be considered.
There are different views about the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the contrary, the US has clearly expressed its preference for the veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European states?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government has a deep-rooted understanding of the European position.
But, of course, due to the local political situation, the Government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that substantial differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, notice that Obama is not at all excited about Netanyahu's policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of a crucial partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for Germans if there was a single, consistent European policy, but it is not now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and have to act instead on their own vision.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take the lead?
Or is Germany still hard to lead?
Germany is not yet accustomed to this, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis — every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings are manifested.
It's not easy for Germans to deal with.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much worse position than the US.
It must take into account a wide range of neighbours and opinions, which is not easy.
So, U.S. influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but the EU is not filling this vacuum right now, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a larger role.
Even if you don't like it, dislike it, or increase dislike for you, that's life.
Stephen Sabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly study the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
"Puma and Armani trademark security" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous trademark, Polo Ralph Lauren, too.
But what is Armani Polo?
It is a completely officially registered name in China that has nothing to do with the firms from whose names it is formed.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names file a lawsuit.
But then it is not clear whether they will be able to defend their rights.
"Foreigners find it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloh, a Taylor Wessing lawyer specializing in trademark rights violations in the Far East.
My desk shows up every week on a new case of this kind.
Simulators only need to add a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci it's Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
In the same way, German enterprises, such as the producer of Puma sports goods, are legally copied.
Pattloch opens a folder with the records of the Trademark Registration Office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, the Chinese company registered the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also uses the name of the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
The fact that the Chinese are world champions of copying and intellectual property rights violations is well known.
In large cities, there are multi-story department stores selling almost exclusively counterfeits.
However, Pattloh's cases were not the same; on behalf of his trustees, he opposed that Chinese enterprises should be officially authorized by the trademark registry to use a name that was already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "ban minpei," the marca passenger.
This word is associated with "ban dakuan".
That's what women who prey on rich men are called.
Chinese authorities do not plead guilty
"It damages business, it needs to be combated," Pattloch is convinced.
"Commerce brand washed, unique position lost, image badly damaged".
Financial losses and procedural costs in affected industries are estimated at millions, especially in the case of expensive copyable products.
According to the CLSA Market Research Company, China, with a sales volume of Euro15 billion per year, is the third largest and fastest growing luxury market.
However, it is difficult and costly to remove questionable entries from the register of trademarks.
The trial may last up to nine years, with an unclear outcome.
Pattloch tells of cases in which the court dismissed the claims because after a long period of time the contested name became "a reality of the market".
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he will even have to pay the plagiarizer because he damaged his trademark in China, Pattloch says.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
There are also famous cases of graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a litigation with the construction vehicle manufacturer Sany, a company that had recently acquired a concrete pump manufacturer, Putzmeister.
Therefore, Chinese still have the right to use a emblem similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo company Geely originally used a blue and white logo that resembled BMW; the process was successful, Geely had to change it.
Lacoste's fashion producer lost in China to simulators from Hong Kong and Singapore, who had a famous crocodile looking the other way.
The Chinese authorities don't think they're guilty.
The Trademark Registration Office of CMMO in Beijing confirms that there were difficulties in 2010 due to lack of staff and facilities.
But last year, there was a "return from emergency in the work process to normal."
Thus, the number of pending cases on objections decreased by 22 per cent.
Almost 57,000 such cases have been closed, 75 per cent more than last year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending in the agency.
It's expensive to fight.
As very often in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CMMO received more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This record means that China has led the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive time, reports the agency.
The same applies to the total number of valid trademarks, only 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan fees were paid.
If simplified, this means that each registration costs an average of 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
It is worth many times more to challenge, as the case of the German family enterprise Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the concern has fought against the Chinese plagiarizer.
The Germans managed to ensure that their illegal production of counterfeit car parts was eliminated.
However, the simulator reserved Chinese trademark rights to Freudenberg.
This was a failure of its own, as surnames in Germany are not protected, says Hanno Ventzler, chairman of the board of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
And the CTMO Trademark Registration Authority rejected the Munich claim.
True, in both of the following instances, Freudenberg won, but the opposing side still continues to fight.
Need to be on guard.
The matter is currently pending before the Supreme Court.
Ventzler hopes to bring the case to a good conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says, "The process is extremely expensive and takes up a lot of time, money and nerves."
Internal costs are hardly measurable, and the firm's archives have had to review even 100 years ago in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg unsuccessfully offered the opposing party a “greater six-digit amount in euros” for a settlement.
"It's clear from here how expensive it is for us," says Wentzler.
The dangers of the Far East threaten to spread even to Europe.
That is, if simulators register unprotected trademarks there.
For example, a Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for footwear and leather products.
The concert had long ceased production in those areas, but had nevertheless been able to prevent registration.
