As Mexico's newly elected President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country's population.
The traffic in Mexico City is in a particularly poor state.
This city is overburdened by transport and at a better time, and steel barriers have been erected since Monday, cutting several key highways to the capital and causing road chaos.
However, this was not done to prevent people from going to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from reaching the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will wear a presidential ligament and take the reins of the country's rule.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico had achieved good economic performance under the Felipe Calderón administration, which was now defusing its powers, but the country had become mired in the war on drugs, which had already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government announces to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence," Mr. Peña Nieto told US President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office of the White House.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve that goal.
Prior to such statements, Mr. Peña Nieto's political career with the President of the United States developed as Governor of his native state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the country's capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
A straight-line person
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, he is remembered with warmth.
Residents have credited him with the revitalization of tourism, the development of resorts and the construction of infrastructure.
The city can be reached on one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which are strikingly different from the bollocks and pits that were previously at the site.
Tables with his name hang on the modern building of the sports centre and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We have hopes for real and serious change with him," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a state congressman from Peña Nieto's institutional-revolutionary party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed by our country, particularly in the areas of security and economic development.
After 81 years of continuous rule, the PRI party was displaced in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, he refutes the allegations of lack of substance that the opposition put forward to the new President.
He is very direct and very committed to the realization of his vision for the future of the country.
It's an excellent statesman, and above all, a man who can listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of a former governor.
The municipality of Nesaualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nesa, is the most striking contrast with the powerful streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under motorway relays, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also severe in this mega-polis.
Earlier this year, troops had been used to curb drug gangs in those areas; violence against women was particularly acute.
Several dozen bodies of murdered women have been found in the desert near an extensive dump in the last two years alone.
More than a thousand women were killed in the state of Mexico City during the governorship of Mr. Peña Nieto, a figure far higher than that in the notorious city of Ciudad Juárez, whose name became negative when it came to the killing of innocent women.
According to Mr. Peña Nieto's opponents, at best he had been unable to cope with the issue of the killing of women during his tenure as Governor.
At worst, his administration is accused of completely ignoring the problem.
A resident of a concrete house similar to most houses in this dilapidated area, Irinaya Buendia has difficulty in holding back tears by showing me pictures of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to Mariana's official version, she committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner killed her.
"When I got to her house, it looked like her body was washed before," recalls Ms. Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten and the body was already hardened.
Mariana's mother recounts this story, and her daughter's portrait looks at us from the wall, where he hangs next to the crucifix, where only one word is inscribed: justice.
This was said to have been denied to the family.
"State officials treated me like an old gossip who was dissatisfied with the troublemaker.
They want people to just accept what they say and keep their mouths shut.
But it's wrong, that's not right, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around," she says.
When President Peña Nieto wears a presidential ligament on Saturday, he will take on a heavy responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico had been affected by violent crimes, and the new President had promised to make the solution of that problem a priority during his reign.
"I hope he'll be the same president as the governor," says Olver, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of victims in Ciudad Nes fear most.
Bradley Manning didn't complain of ill-treatment, pleads charges.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations about poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning's stay at the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions of detention were cruel.
The U.S. Private Army is accused of kidnapping several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, charged with the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, had not taken many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he said he had been able to endure while in a military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mede, Maryland, the military prosecutor, Major Ashden Fein, stated that records of weekly visits to Manning by the prison administration during the nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination, as part of the defence motion to dismiss Manning, on the grounds that his conditions of detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment, was conducted the day after Manning stated that while in detention he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is charged with stealing several thousand secret documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet at WikiLeaks.
The WikiLeaks resource did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the Friday hearing, Prosecutor Fein, along with Manning, reviewed the reports which had been completed after visits to Manning by the administration during his stay at Quantico Prison, where he was under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked Friday about the reports, Manning admitted that he regarded his treatment by the prison administration as "excellent" and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized."
The reports examined do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, even though Manning was explicitly asked about the conditions of his detention, Fane claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concerns about these issues and that the authorities who visited him had discussed these issues with him and stated that they would be dealt with but had not been recorded in writing.
"They recorded "no problems" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in the conversation," Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his ill-treatment in January 2011 during a meeting of the commission considering the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing several months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting, he wanted him to be removed from the "damage warning" regime and to ease the conditions of detention.
The military authorities explained that the limited detention regime, which was lower than the suicide control regime, had been introduced to protect the prisoner as well as the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay with them to cancel the injury prevention regime... so that my life would improve, from my point of view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified to his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had suicide thoughts in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness due to severe heat.
He explained that psychologically it is very difficult when you are not given to know how your fate is decided, and what happens in the outside world.
"My world has come down to Camp-Arifjan base, before the size of my prison," said Manning on Thursday.
- I thought I was gonna die in that cage."
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day - all alone.
Manning reports that he was only allowed to leave his mattress, blanket, spankers, some clothes and glasses.
He says that he tried to move because he was sleeping or even simply being banned from the rules during the day.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly hit in the eye with light coming in from outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he was turning around in bed at night, he said he was woken up and forced to turn on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed an official objection to Manning's ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
Furthermore, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about a statement he had made during his testimony on Thursday that after one night he had been forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he had been forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at the morning check-up.
Manning stated that he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the check.
Responding to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should throw a blanket that could cover himself, but admitted that no one had explicitly ordered him to leave him.
On Thursday, Manning stated that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reported that he told an officer that he could use a pair of panties or spankers to traumatize himself, but he didn't.
That night, according to Manning's testimony, his underwear, flippers and glasses were taken from the cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had experienced during his imprisonment and significantly reduce his sentence, should Manning be found guilty by a military court, which was due to start his case early next year.
The defence has stated that it plans to ask Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and other charges to challenge as excessive.
The resumption of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of detainees under the strictest possible regime.
The charges brought against Manning include aiding and abetting the enemy, illegally facilitating the release of data on the Internet, transmitting information related to national defence, and stealing State property or documents.
If he is convicted on all counts of the indictment, he may be liable to life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is a Mexican-American story.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to a lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes Mexicans of American descent are torn between two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down a corridor for incoming arrivals, approached the border control area and frozen on the spot.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexiconos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (foreigns).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds without knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called Mexican my whole life.
It's just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York think they're Italian.
Later, I stopped at the complex design of "American of Mexican origin."
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's home, there was no need for conditional names or complex designs.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask or answer questions.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of the speakers, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
That's why I got my American passport and lined up for Extranjeros.
I recalled that story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The issues of immigration, drugs and trade, which are familiar to the Presidents of these countries, were on the agenda.
President Peña Nieto was pleased to talk about the recovery of the Mexican economy, which would enable Mexicans to remain in Mexico with the same success instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the US and Canada and create some North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a hard and long-suffering issue.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory at gunpoint.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
So when only a US statesman utters a word of criticism toward Mexico, the press and the elites of Mexican society are immediately complaining that Americans are trespassing on the sovereignty of neighbours.
And Montesuma's descendants are filled with militancy.
However, Mexico's most difficult relationship with more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States is.
Do you want to talk about the offenses?
There's enough of them.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country, and those who do not.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican origin are only for one reason: at some point in their family history, anyone - father or grandfather - was unable to realize himself in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most of the time, they were Mexicans of a certain type - brown, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We're their descendants, and we remember that.
That's not how Mexico sees it.
Today, our lives are the embodiment of the American dream, we have been in good schools and we have found good jobs, but we will not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider as its own.
United States of America.
Moreover, we know that most members of the Mexican elite and ruling class do not like us.
We say the same thing to them.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, like fake Mexicans.
We do not speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failure.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We wouldn't be behind a silk curtain now, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and it reminds me that there is a certain friction between the real Mexicans and Mexican-born Americans - Mexicans are more aware of their national identity, and Mexican-born Americans are offended.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both these countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances of Mexican descent do not feel that they belong to any of them.
We're listening to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
Getting the best of the two worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we're Americans.
And in the United States, they call us Mexicans.
Now, as I learned during my trip, as if our relationship was not yet complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican Americans to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent her interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It's not gonna work.
Too many offenses in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don't think this country is so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-born Americans are still offended by how they treated their relatives in Mexico just recently.
Yeah.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas faction could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
There is a common, senseless debate over who started the first; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip fell in the vicinity of the Israeli capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, while Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly stuck in their eternal conflict, changes have taken place in the Middle East.
This may be viewed in different ways, but the events of the Arab Spring have surrounded many established realities in the rebel storm, and the Palestinians with the Israelis have not been able to stay away from the whirlwind that shocked the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
There are, however, reasons for hope that this deadly impasse will be overcome.
War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on 21 November, is implemented, the clashes this week have only strengthened the positions of the silos on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement that took power in the Gaza Strip in 2007 will claim that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses it suffered.
Although some faction leaders were destroyed and 1.7 million residents blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
The reborn regional leader of Turkey, once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, has supported Hamas; its example has been followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic States in the Persian Gulf.
The solemn supporters of Hamas claim the establishment of an Islamist crescent around Israel, from Lebanon to the north, ruled by a paramilitary group of Hezbollah, to Syria, in which increasingly Islamic rebels are about to overthrow the power of Bashar Assad, and further to Jordan, where the King's authority is threatened by Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of forces in the region occurred on Israel's southern borders, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement was strengthened under President Mohammed Mursi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid no particular attention to supporting Hamas.
On the contrary, Muslim brothers are an organization much similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas can become a significant player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the hardline line in Israel will come to opposite conclusions.
In the military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli Iron Dome missile system has met the cost of its establishment and successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
The citizens of Israel can sleep calmly, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained steadfast; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the last round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, particularly under the Binyamin Netanyahu Government, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Although approximately 30 Israelis have been killed since 2004 by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombings, partly through a wall that enters the West Bank, a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the 22 January elections - has joined forces with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of pandering to the Palestinians and giving them their own State?
If all the power in the West Bank were to be given to them, would they not launch rockets from there towards Israel, as did their fellow Gazans?
It's better to keep them behind the wall and stifling any attempts to lift their heads.
Supporters of the hardline line may win; however, their calculations may be denied in the Arab spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere, do not have the most warm feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defensive part of Israel's budget is greater than that of all its Arab neighbours combined.
The outbreak of war with a regional super-Power is unlikely to help Arab Governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of the President of Egypt, Mursi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel, to no lesser extent, must take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes take place in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression was already undermining the foundations of a democratic order in a Jewish State, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbated those problems.
The bloody operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to be paid for by the growing dissatisfaction of the international community.
Both sides need external momentum
There remains the only solution to which sanctimonious representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper, are relentlessly calling: the formation of two States and Israeli concessions of territories in exchange for security.
It remains to be hoped, not too impressive in the short term, that a ceasefire will enable other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long had to take the decision to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, have the most advantageous position ever to persuade Hamas to accept the borders of the Jewish State adopted since 1967 in the light of the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
That would do more to create a Palestinian State than the forthcoming United Nations vote, which could result in recognition of Palestinian virtual statehood.
President Obama also has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he continues to demonstrate reluctance to engage in the issue.
This is a disastrously short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the Uniform Packaging Act for Cigarettes has entered into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and images of diseased parts of the body are contrasted with sad green boxes similar to all brands of cigarettes.
The first in world practice Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing logos and coloured presentation of different stamps with the same box of sad olives with creepy images of disease-affected parts of the body and images of children whose health was undermined by smoking by their parents.
In addition to the different pictures and inscriptions warning the harm of smoking, the only difference between the packs mandatory from this Saturday is the names of stamps, which are printed in the same small typeface.
These are the harshest conditions in the world for packaging tobacco products.
The Australian Federal Government states that the aim of this measure is to prevent young people from smoking by depriving them of this harmful habit of fashion status.
This decision was based on research that showed that people who had not started smoking before the age of 26 never smoked in 99 cases out of 100.
"It is clear that even at the youngest age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies try to communicate through packaging," explains Health Minister Tanya Plybersek, citing studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia was one of the lowest smokers in the world, so that changes would not affect the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries were already considering doing so.
The tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of the law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This law will have serious consequences other than those conceived by its initiators," says Scott McIntyre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
The producers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply many more of these items for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the other hand, new laws promote business growth.
Sandra Ha of the small family company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for cigarette and silicone cases covering unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (practically from zero) since companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case to a high court in Australia two months ago, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 items to wholesalers and is waiting for a new shipment.
It's a good business for us.
In the view of experts, the popularity of social networks among the target population is a potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures.
Following the adoption of a number of laws in Australia that have made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and their support for sporting events, as well as prohibiting vendors from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian Government has prohibited local companies and websites from placing advertisements online, but it cannot limit overseas websites.
"If you're selling tobacco and you have only this small loophole left, the idea of promoting your product on the Internet will seem very tempting to you," explains Becky Freeman, investigating public health issues at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increasing number of brand reviews written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook.
The question is, is it really the work of a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he didn't spare his energy and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind it?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry has even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these States are making claims within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that all these countries have very little trade relations with Australia.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plybersek, the Government was discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory smoking-awareness photos.
The rule is now in place in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstratingly disobeying innovations.
These pictures don't bother me.
I just don't pay attention.
"Just taking a cigarette and hiding a pack in your pocket," explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a photograph of a mouth tumor on a pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can get me to leave is my little daughter.
James Yew, head of the tobacco store King of the Pack in downtown Sydney, claims that the same package made it more difficult to place goods in shelves.
"I've had an hour to unload a new party and now four hours," he complains.
"The government should have taken and banned cigarettes altogether, we would have said, 'What do we do, okay, it's over, we close the store," he says, throwing his hands up.
Boring the world of electronic networks and regular connections is not so bad.
On Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had mechanical malfunctions and was replaced by another plane that we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I won't lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books, magazines, iPhones, nor even duty-free shops will help much.
However, more and more scholars and child development professionals have recently expressed their preference for boredom.
They say that in certain situations, it's not so bad for us and our children to miss.
This causes the brain to become distracted by interesting related topics, which may be conducive to creativity.
And since in today's world we're all constantly in front of a screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we should seek boredom.
Yeah.
At the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think, like many people, that boredom was an invention of the recent times when people had more free time.
This is not the case, claims Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at Calgary University of Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact, boredom can boast of a very ancient history," he says.
The walls in Pompeii contain Latin inscriptions of boredom dating back to the first century.
The question remains, however, as to how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, Associate Professor, University of York in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying the research on the subject and asking a 100-member target group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people “want but cannot do what would satisfy them”.
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn't do anything that he would like to do.
I don't want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing in the boredom, he says, is "a breakdown of attention and the resulting deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is running slow."
The description of boredom may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these states, bored people see the causes of the problems in the surrounding world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see the problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored when it's just hard to focus on something.
In his study "The Unoccupied Mind: Defining Boring from a Attention Point", published in September's issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment, where participants listened to a recording of a voice reading the magazine.
Some participants also heard loud sounds of a unrelated television program included in the next room, others heard the same sounds on low volume, so that they could barely be addressed, and a third group listened only to recording the voice without a foreign sound track.
Those who heard low-volume television said that they were bored, more often others - they found it difficult to concentrate, but they did not know the reason and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "e.g. by looking at the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom."
It is believed that he continues that when people start rocking on a chair or drawing doodles on a piece of paper, they do so out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions just help not to relax physically.
"Studies have shown that children who are not prohibited from twirling and spinning learn better and remember more information than children who are asked to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we're all bored with a delayed flight (as in my case), listening to a monotonic speech, watching an uninteresting film.
However, different people show different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, in order to measure such individual features, researchers developed a special "sorry-like scale".
Questions and assertions such as “Many things I have to do are uniform and monotonous” or “I'm too interested, so I don't have time for anything” are used to measure this scale.
Through such questionnaires, researchers have determined that boys miss more girls, says Stephen Vodovic, a psychology professor at the University of Western Florida, especially when there are a variety of external irritants.
However, in general, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment during which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day with the help of a pager.
He obtained the following results: 32 per cent of adolescents said they were bored in school and during their homework, and 23 per cent said they were bored outside of school.
However, only 3 percent of parents indicated that they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data would be about boredom now, 21 years later.
