The hardest job in the world: Kawah-Igen miners
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk life and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulphur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky trails
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
These include Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who earn a living from sulphur mining in the Kawah Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes in contact with the air.
The pieces are huge pieces of sulphur, which can weigh as much as 70 kg in total, and he puts them in two bamboo baskets, lifts the baskets on his shoulders, and carries them up the cliffed stone road.
To the summit of the volcano, which is 2,386 metres high, only 250 metres are required, but it takes more than 40 minutes for the worn-out loaders to rise up with a turtle step, struggling with balance and cautiously groping the road so as not to fall or fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong move could cost them their lives, as happened to a tourist from France who fell off the Kawah-Igen Rocks a few years ago.
The Kawah-Igen mine earns 5 Euro cents per kilogram of sulphur that is extracted
Once they are at the top, they pave the way for themselves between tourists who are photographed as if they were circus monkeys and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometres to the scales that the mining company has placed just above, at a height of 1.850 metres.
This is the PT Kandi Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has operated this volcano since 1960 and, better not to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Euro cents) for each kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for Rs. 10,000 (83 Euro cents) petrochemical production, as this mineral is common in daily life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"As the standard is to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per walk," Anto explains to us, who usually performs three daily transports.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138.000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems a miser for such a non-human effort, it's three times what he would have earned in the field.
" The daily wage for miners is very high by local standards, where the coffee charge is Rs. 15,000 (€1.2) per day and the average monthly wage is Rs. 2 million (€167), " explains the loader who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
His salary there was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the plot was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family in Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a valid reason which in Indonesia is as devastating as sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where only Hindus, and brought her to Java to accept Islam."
Anto's asthma, he's barely breathing, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are tearing because of toxic gases.
At his 27-year-old age, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah Igen, whose sulphur had already begun to affect him despite having a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, he coughs constantly, and his eyes cry because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
It's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work for two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, a waiter or a hotel doorman, but instead he does the work of a mule.
A dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at 2:00 a.m. because sulphur doesn't stop flowing out at night when her distinctive yellow color turns blue and glitters in the middle of the darkness.
By challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, lighting his way with a small lamp connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters haul baskets of grey on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano.
Despite high profits, the mining company did not mechanize sulphur mining to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such hardship.
In fact, they do not even receive part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) charge for photography, which, along with an entry ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), guards of this reserve charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mule men.
"This work is for livestock, not people," says Badrusin, a 42-year-old native porter who spent three decades in Kawah Ijena since leaving college.
Capable of up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will endure the job "as long as he can" because he needs money to educate his three children between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm gonna die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur burns its throat and burns its eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches miners in dense pillars of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so resilient that no one complains of their severe diseases... more serious, obviously than their usual breathing problems, arthrose, knee pains and shoulder ulcer, which deformed under the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unanik can only lift 50 kilograms in his 53s.
Each day, he and his companions carry 15 tons of sulphur out of the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, crossing a distance of 18 kilometres along a narrow trail among the bushes.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life," says Unanik, wide-opening a mouth that lacks a few teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30 years old, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest jobs in the world: what human mules do with Kawah Igen.
