UNASUR summit ends without the Lima Declaration
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to a document signed at the sixth ordinary meeting of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the Office of the President indicated on the front page that it would be transmitted after closure, but then confirmed that it would be published on the Peruvian Government website at some point.
Questions about the text, they pointed out that the contents had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Umala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists ' access to Summit information has been limited all the time.
During the day, it was only broadcast, in the press room, a video of the Presidential Assembly without a sound, with the message "closed meeting, sound forbidden".
Few of the information that has been distributed to reporters has been conveyed by spokespersons of some UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not Peruvian.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused dissatisfaction among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian President's administration sent an e-mail to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but it was a statement by Umala, not an official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and that time, despite the insistence of the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was also not distributed.
The ASPA official website can verify that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities had endeavoured to ensure that all journalists were provided with transmission systems, but that information was as limited as possible.
The Summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt the verdict of the Hague Court, which settles the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Piñera, gathered at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which starts hearing the statements of both parties on Monday in The Hague, as part of the accusation that Lima has made against Santiago.
"We will observe and implement a decision that will explain the differences that we are currently submitting to this international court," Umala said, next to his Chilean colleague.
“Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of differences, covenants and international tribunals”, added Piñera, and welcomed the hand of Umala against the background of the flags of those two countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they would be subject to the International Court of Justice occurred immediately after Colombia protested this week the Pact of Bogotá, according to which it recognized the subordination of the verdicts of that international court to the maritime boundary with Nicaragua, which it considered to be erroneous.
The summit took place in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Roussef; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Olianta Umala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon in Lima time.
The Head of State read the outcome document, in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects had been approved among South American countries, with an estimated investment of $17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would take “important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residence agreements”.
He reported that action was being taken to improve “cooperation in the fight against citizens' insecurity and organized transnational crime, actions to increase access to medicines, low-cost Internet access in all parts of South America and to take into account the combined and effective risks of natural disasters”.
As Europe is in crisis, "the economic union (Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our production base and anticipate a better future for our cities," added Umala.
"We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South America's spaces, especially in the village and border zones... unifying our countries and forming new economic schemes," said the Peruvian president in a read-through.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five related to Peru and were limited to transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide further details.
The outcome document also addressed the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve as a re-accession to the Union of South American Nations, from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united and to have good relations between neighbours, was another theme emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before taking part in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate in a respectful manner the maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of the international court challenged by Bogotá.
"The day after tomorrow (Saturday), perhaps to meet President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
“Let us reconsider all these ways, they are not mutually exclusive, including a pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua”, he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we can handle this in the most civil and respectful manner possible," added Santos.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they will have a presence at the inauguration of the new President of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also within the framework of the summit, the Ministers of Defence of the bloc met provisionally to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which is aimed at strengthening dialogue and consensus on the protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the latter has been suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
